WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.820 --> 00:00:07.820
Hi everyone, I'm Sam from the FreeWings flight school

2
00:00:07.820 --> 00:00:11.820
and today I'll be going through the topic of flight practice with you.

3
00:00:11.820 --> 00:00:15.820
Flight practice — and what we set up here, whether outside or in the classroom,

4
00:00:15.820 --> 00:00:17.820
doesn't quite all fit together yet.

5
00:00:17.820 --> 00:00:22.300
What we do is first build up our own knowledge.

6
00:00:22.300 --> 00:00:26.300
And we have to — or rather, we should — do that with solid theory.

7
00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:29.300
Once we know the theory, we can apply it well.

8
00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:33.300
And once we've trained the application, we get into the realm of being able to do it.

9
00:00:33.300 --> 00:01:03.300
And only along that path does it really work.

10
00:01:03.300 --> 00:01:05.300
We're aiming for 100% correct answers.

11
00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:09.300
For all of this, when looking at flight practice,

12
00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.300
it helps to picture the whole thing in the context of a real flight.

13
00:01:12.300 --> 00:01:14.300
Speaking of which,

14
00:01:14.300 --> 00:01:16.300
it actually starts at home.

15
00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:20.550
A flight is something you have to prepare for.

16
00:01:20.550 --> 00:01:24.550
It's usually not a good idea to head straight to the launch site

17
00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:27.550
without having done your homework beforehand.

18
00:01:27.550 --> 00:01:30.550
Then you get surprised by something at the launch.

19
00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:30.590
And if you've already

20
00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:33.550
thought through at home what you actually want to do,

21
00:01:33.550 --> 00:01:36.550
it makes things much, much easier.

22
00:01:36.550 --> 00:01:39.550
And the first thing that belongs to that

23
00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:42.550
is asking yourself: am I actually fit to fly?

24
00:01:42.550 --> 00:01:45.550
That means knowing what kind of shape I'm in,

25
00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:49.550
whether I'm mentally clear, whether I had any kind of bender

26
00:01:49.550 --> 00:01:52.550
the night before and have a hangover.

27
00:01:52.550 --> 00:01:55.550
Am I fit, have I taken any medication

28
00:01:55.550 --> 00:01:57.550
because maybe I have some pain

29
00:01:57.550 --> 00:01:58.550
I'm trying to suppress?

30
00:02:28.810 --> 00:02:31.810
It's all different from what I expected.

31
00:02:31.810 --> 00:02:33.810
What I'm getting at is: I have to know

32
00:02:33.810 --> 00:02:36.810
what a front is, and I have to know

33
00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:38.810
what foehn is.

34
00:02:38.810 --> 00:02:41.810
And if one of these three weather topics shows up,

35
00:02:41.810 --> 00:02:47.030
my ears need to perk up and I have to ask: what's actually going on?

36
00:02:47.030 --> 00:02:52.030
Because, as I know, a front — and also foehn especially —

37
00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:55.030
usually brings a lot of wind with it.

38
00:02:55.030 --> 00:02:58.030
Strong wind is always pretty bad for paragliding,

39
00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:01.030
because we're flying relatively slowly.

40
00:03:01.030 --> 00:03:04.420
Foehn in general is a dangerous situation,

41
00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:07.420
where as a student you don't go up in the air.

42
00:03:07.420 --> 00:03:09.420
Later, when you're very experienced,

43
00:03:09.420 --> 00:03:11.420
there are geographical spots

44
00:03:11.420 --> 00:03:13.420
where you can fly even in foehn,

45
00:03:13.420 --> 00:03:16.420
but you need a lot of prior knowledge for that.

46
00:03:16.420 --> 00:03:19.420
Same thing for thunderstorms,

47
00:03:19.420 --> 00:03:21.420
where you need a lot of experience.

48
00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:25.420
Generally, with thunder clouds and front clouds,

49
00:03:25.420 --> 00:03:29.420
these are situations you mostly don't want to be in.

50
00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:33.430
Then it's important

51
00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:38.560
that you've also looked into the regulatory side.

52
00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:41.560
There are paragliding maps

53
00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:44.560
that show us the legal situation.

54
00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:46.560
And there are airspace restrictions,

55
00:03:46.560 --> 00:03:49.560
which can be pretty harsh if you don't know about them.

56
00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:51.560
And for airspace restrictions,

57
00:03:51.560 --> 00:03:52.560
to stay informed,

58
00:03:52.560 --> 00:03:55.560
you have to check, every single flying day,

59
00:03:55.560 --> 00:03:57.560
the daily NOTAMs

60
00:03:57.560 --> 00:04:00.560
to see if any current airspace restrictions are in place.

61
00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:02.560
Some of these can be quite large,

62
00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:05.560
like for example the World Economic Forum in Davos,

63
00:04:05.560 --> 00:04:08.560
where the airspace gets very heavily restricted.

64
00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:09.560
And I can imagine

65
00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:10.560
that there too,

66
00:04:10.560 --> 00:04:12.560
if you fly in,

67
00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:14.560
you'd get an escort pretty quickly

68
00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:16.560
from much bigger aircraft.

69
00:04:16.560 --> 00:04:17.560
So as a paraglider

70
00:04:17.560 --> 00:04:18.560
it's not exactly clever

71
00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:19.560
to fly in there.

72
00:04:19.560 --> 00:04:21.560
But there are also smaller restrictions.

73
00:04:21.560 --> 00:04:23.560
We have a meeting,

74
00:04:23.560 --> 00:04:25.560
for example at a regional event site,

75
00:04:25.560 --> 00:04:26.560
it's full of people,

76
00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:27.560
and there's a cylinder

77
00:04:27.560 --> 00:04:29.560
where it's also forbidden

78
00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:30.560
to fly over,

79
00:04:30.560 --> 00:04:31.560
because it's very big,

80
00:04:31.560 --> 00:04:32.560
with a gathering of people.

81
00:04:32.560 --> 00:04:34.560
This information you'll find

82
00:04:34.560 --> 00:04:36.560
described pretty well in the NOTAMs.

83
00:04:36.560 --> 00:04:39.560
And then you also have to think about

84
00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:40.560
where you want

85
00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:42.560
to fly — for example on a cross-country flight.

86
00:04:42.560 --> 00:04:44.560
Then military flight operations

87
00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:46.560
are important — military aviation services —

88
00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:48.560
and you need to know about them,

89
00:04:48.560 --> 00:04:50.690
because depending on the case,

90
00:04:50.690 --> 00:04:52.690
you might be able to fly higher,

91
00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:54.690
since the military

92
00:04:54.690 --> 00:04:56.690
— on a weekend

93
00:04:56.690 --> 00:04:57.690
is calmer

94
00:04:57.690 --> 00:04:59.690
than, for example, during the week.

95
00:04:59.690 --> 00:05:01.690
Another part of all of this

96
00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:03.690
is checking your gear,

97
00:05:03.690 --> 00:05:04.690
making sure

98
00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:05.690
that the gear

99
00:05:05.690 --> 00:05:06.690
you've got with you

100
00:05:06.690 --> 00:05:07.690
works.

101
00:05:07.690 --> 00:05:08.690
That includes, for example,

102
00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:10.690
charging the battery.

103
00:05:10.690 --> 00:05:11.690
It's no use

104
00:05:11.690 --> 00:05:12.690
if you end up in an emergency

105
00:05:12.690 --> 00:05:14.690
and your phone has died,

106
00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:17.690
then you can't share anything,

107
00:05:17.690 --> 00:05:20.690
because in such a case

108
00:05:20.690 --> 00:05:22.730
we can really —

109
00:05:22.730 --> 00:05:28.850
since we have the restriction

110
00:05:28.850 --> 00:05:31.690
of many being in the same context —

111
00:05:31.690 --> 00:05:33.690
all of that

112
00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.130
we can use continuously,

113
00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:36.970
and it helps,

114
00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:39.690
for instance, with talking.

115
00:05:39.690 --> 00:05:41.690
There's also a feeding task,

116
00:05:41.690 --> 00:05:44.690
and so on in front of the preparation,

117
00:05:44.690 --> 00:05:45.690
where we restrict ourselves.

118
00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:53.690
While packing up — if you somehow landed in muck and the wing sat in the trunk of the car for a week,

119
00:05:53.690 --> 00:05:54.690
where it's warm.

120
00:05:54.690 --> 00:06:00.690
Those are all things that later shorten the life of the material and aren't good for the wing.

121
00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:02.690
And when you unpack,

122
00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:03.690
(unclear)

123
00:06:03.690 --> 00:06:06.850
if it's not what you were expecting, you think about it.

124
00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:12.850
Also important — take provisions with you, make sure you've got enough to drink.

125
00:06:12.850 --> 00:06:14.850
Drinking is essential.

126
00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:16.850
Drinking, drinking, you've got to be a super drinker.

127
00:06:18.850 --> 00:06:29.170
Drinking — drinking — going along with that, of course,

128
00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:31.170
for example with a urinal condom,

129
00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:34.170
where you can also urinate in the air.

130
00:06:34.170 --> 00:06:36.170
And for women there are diapers too.

131
00:06:36.170 --> 00:06:39.170
And you can get the problem under control.

132
00:06:39.170 --> 00:06:43.170
But it's not smart to skip drinking because of the problem.

133
00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:45.170
Drinking is really important.

134
00:06:45.170 --> 00:06:47.170
It helps with concentration.

135
00:06:47.170 --> 00:06:48.170
It keeps you fit.

136
00:06:48.170 --> 00:06:51.170
And at the end of the flying day

137
00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:53.170
a nasty headache can come up,

138
00:06:53.170 --> 00:06:57.670
which you can get if you've had too little to drink.

139
00:06:57.670 --> 00:07:00.670
Then, once you've done all the preparations,

140
00:07:00.670 --> 00:07:03.670
it makes sense to drive to the flying area

141
00:07:03.670 --> 00:07:05.670
and have a quick look at the landing site.

142
00:07:05.670 --> 00:07:07.670
We were at the landing site,

143
00:07:07.670 --> 00:07:10.020
and quite obviously,

144
00:07:10.020 --> 00:07:13.020
because you have relatively little altitude,

145
00:07:13.020 --> 00:07:15.020
you start looking for it.

146
00:07:15.020 --> 00:07:17.020
And then it's good if you already know it.

147
00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:19.020
That means scouting out the landing site

148
00:07:19.020 --> 00:07:21.020
really does make sense.

149
00:07:21.020 --> 00:07:22.020
We can already check

150
00:07:22.020 --> 00:07:24.020
where there are public obstacles,

151
00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:26.020
such as cables,

152
00:07:26.020 --> 00:07:29.020
that run nearby, across the valley.

153
00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:31.020
Where there's, say, a big tree

154
00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:34.020
you might need to watch out for.

155
00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:36.020
And how we want to land at all

156
00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:37.020
is something to look at in detail.

157
00:07:37.020 --> 00:07:39.020
There are good aids for that.

158
00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:41.020
Namely, mostly the local pilots,

159
00:07:41.020 --> 00:07:43.020
who know how the landing pattern goes.

160
00:07:43.020 --> 00:07:45.020
Cricket — sorry, the wing area.

161
00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:47.020
The standard pattern is a left-hand pattern.

162
00:07:47.020 --> 00:07:49.020
But depending on conditions

163
00:07:49.020 --> 00:07:51.020
at the landing site, it can vary

164
00:07:51.020 --> 00:07:53.020
and be a right-hand pattern instead.

165
00:07:53.020 --> 00:07:54.020
Depending on wind conditions.

166
00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:56.020
That's usually well marked

167
00:07:56.020 --> 00:07:58.020
at the landing site,

168
00:07:58.020 --> 00:07:59.020
clearly visible.

169
00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:00.020
If not,

170
00:08:00.020 --> 00:08:01.020
ask the locals.

171
00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:03.310
Also important

172
00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:04.310
is that you know

173
00:08:04.310 --> 00:08:05.310
where you'll actually be flying.

174
00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:07.310
We do a bit of flight planning.

175
00:08:07.310 --> 00:08:08.310
When you're at the landing site,

176
00:08:08.310 --> 00:08:09.310
we can check

177
00:08:09.310 --> 00:08:10.310
where the launch site is,

178
00:08:10.310 --> 00:08:11.310
usually.

179
00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:14.310
And where there might be an emergency landing field.

180
00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:16.310
If the landing site were closed,

181
00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:17.310
it could be

182
00:08:17.310 --> 00:08:18.310
that something has happened

183
00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:19.310
and they're picking up an injured hiker.

184
00:08:19.310 --> 00:08:20.310
As I mentioned,

185
00:08:20.310 --> 00:08:23.310
the rescue helicopter lands right on the landing field.

186
00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:24.310
It's important

187
00:08:24.310 --> 00:08:25.310
that you know

188
00:08:25.310 --> 00:08:26.310
where you'd land.

189
00:08:26.310 --> 00:08:28.380
And then there are other things

190
00:08:28.380 --> 00:08:29.380
we have to think about,

191
00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:31.380
regarding turbulence,

192
00:08:31.380 --> 00:08:32.380
say there are big

193
00:08:32.380 --> 00:08:34.380
trees there,

194
00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:35.380
that can cause turbulence,

195
00:08:35.380 --> 00:08:37.380
in moderate wind,

196
00:08:37.380 --> 00:08:38.380
which could surprise us

197
00:08:38.380 --> 00:08:39.380
and disturb the landing.

198
00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:42.380
Doing all these mental preparations

199
00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:44.380
makes the flight

200
00:08:44.380 --> 00:08:45.380
much, much easier overall,

201
00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.380
because you've got a plan B in your head,

202
00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:50.380
and having a plan B is already very important.

203
00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:52.380
We never go on a new flight

204
00:08:52.380 --> 00:08:53.380
without knowing

205
00:08:53.380 --> 00:08:54.380
what we'll do

206
00:08:54.380 --> 00:08:55.380
if it doesn't go

207
00:08:55.380 --> 00:08:56.380
the way we thought,

208
00:08:56.380 --> 00:08:58.380
always have preparation lined up

209
00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:00.380
for the what-ifs.

210
00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:02.180
On top of that comes

211
00:09:02.180 --> 00:09:04.180
the consideration

212
00:09:04.180 --> 00:09:05.180
regarding wildlife.

213
00:09:05.180 --> 00:09:07.180
Wildlife protection

214
00:09:07.180 --> 00:09:08.180
is a big topic.

215
00:09:08.180 --> 00:09:09.180
In the past we'd always

216
00:09:09.180 --> 00:09:10.180
go into the debate

217
00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:11.180
where today we say

218
00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:12.180
the paraglider flight

219
00:09:12.180 --> 00:09:14.180
passing through the wildlife

220
00:09:14.180 --> 00:09:16.180
— a new study suggests

221
00:09:16.180 --> 00:09:17.180
(and now it comes at a cost),

222
00:09:17.180 --> 00:09:18.180
shows actually

223
00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:19.180
the opposite,

224
00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:20.180
that the paraglider pilot

225
00:09:20.180 --> 00:09:22.180
does carry some responsibility,

226
00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:24.180
has to take wildlife into account,

227
00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:25.180
and it's really important

228
00:09:25.180 --> 00:09:26.180
to pay attention.

229
00:09:26.180 --> 00:09:27.180
We have a site

230
00:09:27.180 --> 00:09:29.180
where local wildlife information

231
00:09:29.180 --> 00:09:30.180
is usually on the info board

232
00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:32.180
described, mostly at the lift station,

233
00:09:32.180 --> 00:09:33.180
where, for example, areas

234
00:09:33.180 --> 00:09:34.180
that we shouldn't fly over at all

235
00:09:34.180 --> 00:09:35.180
are listed.

236
00:09:35.180 --> 00:09:37.180
But it's also important

237
00:09:37.180 --> 00:09:38.180
to have a basic idea

238
00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:40.180
about wildlife in general.

239
00:09:40.180 --> 00:09:41.180
And in the theory

240
00:09:41.180 --> 00:09:43.180
we know for this topic,

241
00:09:43.180 --> 00:09:44.180
there are also lots

242
00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:46.180
of questions about wildlife protection.

243
00:09:46.180 --> 00:09:48.180
It's about, for example,

244
00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:49.180
the issue of

245
00:09:49.180 --> 00:09:50.180
when animals have

246
00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:52.180
their young,

247
00:09:52.180 --> 00:09:54.180
since exactly during that time —

248
00:09:54.180 --> 00:09:55.180
namely in spring

249
00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:57.180
and in spring

250
00:09:57.180 --> 00:09:59.180
we have beautiful flying.

251
00:09:59.180 --> 00:10:00.180
That means

252
00:10:00.180 --> 00:10:01.180
we end up at those places

253
00:10:01.180 --> 00:10:02.180
where, for example, eagles,

254
00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:04.180
chamois and ibex

255
00:10:04.180 --> 00:10:07.180
raise their young.

256
00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:08.180
For eagles,

257
00:10:08.180 --> 00:10:09.180
you have to expect, from March

258
00:10:09.180 --> 00:10:11.180
through May,

259
00:10:11.180 --> 00:10:13.180
that they're sitting on the nest

260
00:10:13.180 --> 00:10:15.180
and also defending their territory.

261
00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:17.180
For chamois it's in May,

262
00:10:17.180 --> 00:10:19.180
and for ibex

263
00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:21.180
it's in June.

264
00:10:21.180 --> 00:10:22.180
And during that time,

265
00:10:22.180 --> 00:10:23.180
if the animals are there,

266
00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.180
fly away.

267
00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:26.180
It's simply fair

268
00:10:26.180 --> 00:10:27.180
toward the animals,

269
00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:29.180
that you don't say something like

270
00:10:29.180 --> 00:10:30.180
"it's safe to stay,"

271
00:10:30.180 --> 00:10:31.180
or "the thermal is"

272
00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:32.180
particularly good,"

273
00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:33.180
"I don't care"

274
00:10:33.180 --> 00:10:34.180
if there are three chamois below,

275
00:10:34.180 --> 00:10:35.180
but instead — fly away.

276
00:10:35.180 --> 00:10:36.180
The animals already

277
00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:37.180
have enough stress

278
00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:39.180
from all the environmental pressure,

279
00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:40.180
so on top of that

280
00:10:40.180 --> 00:10:41.180
paragliding pilots

281
00:10:41.180 --> 00:10:42.180
who claim to love nature

282
00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:44.180
shouldn't add to the stress.

283
00:10:44.180 --> 00:10:46.010
As already mentioned,

284
00:10:46.010 --> 00:10:47.010
the local specifics

285
00:10:47.010 --> 00:10:49.010
of individual wildlife sanctuaries,

286
00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:51.010
are mostly clearly readable

287
00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:54.010
and posted at the stations.

288
00:10:54.010 --> 00:10:55.010
And here too:

289
00:10:55.010 --> 00:10:56.010
ask

290
00:10:56.010 --> 00:10:57.010
— not just look,

291
00:10:57.010 --> 00:10:59.010
but ask local people,

292
00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:01.010
they're always happy to share.

293
00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:05.700
When you get to the mountain,

294
00:11:05.700 --> 00:11:07.700
right to the launch site,

295
00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:09.820
it's like this for many,

296
00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:10.820
that there's already a bit

297
00:11:10.820 --> 00:11:12.820
of butterflies in your stomach.

298
00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:13.820
Having a few butterflies

299
00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:15.820
is actually a good sign,

300
00:11:15.820 --> 00:11:18.820
because it means you're taking things seriously.

301
00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:20.820
And especially when

302
00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:22.820
you don't know a launch site,

303
00:11:22.820 --> 00:11:24.820
for example a tricky flight,

304
00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:25.820
going to a launch

305
00:11:25.820 --> 00:11:27.820
you don't know at all,

306
00:11:27.820 --> 00:11:28.820
it's all the more important

307
00:11:28.820 --> 00:11:30.820
to have a guiding principle there,

308
00:11:30.820 --> 00:11:31.820
which is reported there,

309
00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:32.820
to apply

310
00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:33.820
and so on,

311
00:11:33.820 --> 00:11:34.820
at every launch site.

312
00:11:34.820 --> 00:11:35.820
It must always be

313
00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:36.820
possible,

314
00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:37.820
ideally until liftoff,

315
00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:38.820
to abort the launch.

316
00:11:38.820 --> 00:11:41.080
If we launch from a cliff

317
00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:42.080
edge,

318
00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:44.080
where you've only got a little run-up

319
00:11:44.080 --> 00:11:46.080
and then it drops off into a big void,

320
00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:48.080
that's definitely not the abort phase,

321
00:11:48.080 --> 00:11:49.080
and it's also

322
00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:50.080
not the right launch site.

323
00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:53.080
Naturally, depending

324
00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:54.080
on the pilot,

325
00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:55.080
the boundary shifts a bit.

326
00:11:55.080 --> 00:11:56.080
But the guiding rule

327
00:11:56.080 --> 00:11:58.080
applies to everyone, always.

328
00:11:58.080 --> 00:12:01.420
Then of course we have

329
00:12:01.420 --> 00:12:02.420
different criteria

330
00:12:02.420 --> 00:12:03.420
for the launch site.

331
00:12:03.420 --> 00:12:04.420
When we arrive,

332
00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:05.420
we first have to

333
00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:07.420
figure out what kind of wind we have at home base.

334
00:12:07.420 --> 00:12:08.420
If we naturally

335
00:12:08.420 --> 00:12:09.420
have downwind,

336
00:12:09.420 --> 00:12:10.420
meaning tailwind,

337
00:12:10.420 --> 00:12:11.420
at the launch,

338
00:12:11.420 --> 00:12:12.420
we definitely need

339
00:12:12.420 --> 00:12:13.420
the kind of launch site

340
00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:14.420
where you can run

341
00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:15.420
for a long way.

342
00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:16.420
Meaning:

343
00:12:16.420 --> 00:12:17.420
behind us is clear,

344
00:12:17.420 --> 00:12:18.420
we can't have to weave between

345
00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:19.420
and run through.

346
00:12:19.420 --> 00:12:20.420
Instead we check

347
00:12:20.420 --> 00:12:21.420
that the area

348
00:12:21.420 --> 00:12:22.420
behind us is free,

349
00:12:22.420 --> 00:12:23.420
so we can accelerate

350
00:12:23.420 --> 00:12:25.420
and at takeoff

351
00:12:25.420 --> 00:12:27.420
still carry speed,

352
00:12:27.420 --> 00:12:28.420
and that behind us is clear.

353
00:12:28.420 --> 00:12:29.420
And it's good

354
00:12:29.420 --> 00:12:30.420
when we find the launch site

355
00:12:30.420 --> 00:12:31.420
in a state

356
00:12:31.420 --> 00:12:33.420
where there's a slight updraft,

357
00:12:33.420 --> 00:12:35.420
the situation looks naturally different.

358
00:12:35.420 --> 00:12:36.420
Then we can do a beautiful

359
00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:37.420
wing in the row

360
00:12:37.420 --> 00:12:39.420
and a reverse launch.

361
00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:40.420
And then we can

362
00:12:40.420 --> 00:12:41.420
start with

363
00:12:41.420 --> 00:12:43.420
a wing with strong sail,

364
00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:44.420
the wing builders

365
00:12:44.420 --> 00:12:45.420
running into it,

366
00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:46.420
uphill into the slope.

367
00:12:46.420 --> 00:12:47.420
That means

368
00:12:47.420 --> 00:12:48.420
we have to make sure

369
00:12:48.420 --> 00:12:50.420
that behind us,

370
00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:51.420
or also toward the wing,

371
00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:52.420
there are no obstacles,

372
00:12:52.420 --> 00:12:53.420
so we don't stumble.

373
00:12:53.420 --> 00:12:54.420
The same applies

374
00:12:54.420 --> 00:12:55.420
with tailwind:

375
00:12:55.420 --> 00:12:56.420
if we have

376
00:12:56.420 --> 00:12:57.420
a bit of tailwind,

377
00:12:57.420 --> 00:12:58.420
then maybe we'll need to

378
00:12:58.420 --> 00:12:59.420
pull the wing up against the wind

379
00:12:59.420 --> 00:13:00.420
and then a small arc

380
00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:02.420
and run in the fall line.

381
00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:03.420
And then ideally

382
00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:05.420
there should be no obstacles.

383
00:13:05.420 --> 00:13:07.420
And that's an important

384
00:13:07.420 --> 00:13:09.420
criterion for the launch site.

385
00:13:09.420 --> 00:13:12.420
Also part of that is people gathering,

386
00:13:12.420 --> 00:13:14.420
especially at a public launch site

387
00:13:14.420 --> 00:13:15.420
where the lift drops people off,

388
00:13:15.420 --> 00:13:17.420
you get lots of spectators very quickly,

389
00:13:17.420 --> 00:13:19.420
the spectators are on one hand

390
00:13:19.420 --> 00:13:20.420
nice,

391
00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:21.420
watching our sport,

392
00:13:21.420 --> 00:13:22.420
looking on,

393
00:13:22.420 --> 00:13:23.420
but on the other hand

394
00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:24.420
they're a distraction.

395
00:13:24.420 --> 00:13:25.420
Meaning:

396
00:13:25.420 --> 00:13:26.420
they'll maybe

397
00:13:26.420 --> 00:13:27.420
talk to you,

398
00:13:27.420 --> 00:13:28.460
they'll

399
00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:29.460
want answers to questions,

400
00:13:29.460 --> 00:13:30.460
and the whole thing

401
00:13:30.460 --> 00:13:31.460
distracts you.

402
00:13:31.460 --> 00:13:32.460
So maybe make sure

403
00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:33.460
at the launch site

404
00:13:33.460 --> 00:13:34.460
to be the two people,

405
00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:35.460
those who keep calm,

406
00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:36.460
especially when you're not sure

407
00:13:36.460 --> 00:13:37.460
of yourself,

408
00:13:37.460 --> 00:13:38.460
those who can still ignore you a bit.

409
00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:40.460
From the whole launch site

410
00:13:40.460 --> 00:13:42.650
we take our time,

411
00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:43.650
create the calm,

412
00:13:43.650 --> 00:13:44.650
never hectic,

413
00:13:44.650 --> 00:13:45.650
and then

414
00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:52.300
you also get a great launch.

415
00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:54.300
When you're ready

416
00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.300
to go for the launch,

417
00:13:56.300 --> 00:13:58.300
one thing is indispensable:

418
00:13:58.300 --> 00:13:59.300
namely that we do a good

419
00:13:59.300 --> 00:14:00.300
pre-launch check.

420
00:14:00.300 --> 00:14:01.300
And the check,

421
00:14:01.300 --> 00:14:02.300
that we've got it,

422
00:14:02.300 --> 00:14:03.300
even if it's never been ingrained yet,

423
00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:04.300
for sure,

424
00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:05.300
is something you already learn there,

425
00:14:05.300 --> 00:14:06.300
it's a really big topic

426
00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:07.300
in the theory,

427
00:14:07.300 --> 00:14:08.300
and you see

428
00:14:08.300 --> 00:14:10.300
everyone doing a kind of stick-and-move.

429
00:14:10.300 --> 00:14:12.300
We catch ourselves through the whole thing,

430
00:14:12.300 --> 00:14:13.300
actually

431
00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:14.300
when the harness is laid out on the ground,

432
00:14:14.300 --> 00:14:15.300
we pick it up,

433
00:14:15.300 --> 00:14:16.300
put it on,

434
00:14:16.300 --> 00:14:17.300
as already shown,

435
00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:18.300
and now

436
00:14:18.300 --> 00:14:19.300
the great control

437
00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:20.300
is,

438
00:14:20.300 --> 00:14:21.300
the reserve handle

439
00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:22.300
is set inside the harness,

440
00:14:22.300 --> 00:14:24.300
are the two split pins

441
00:14:24.300 --> 00:14:25.300
set properly,

442
00:14:25.300 --> 00:14:26.300
the two pins,

443
00:14:26.300 --> 00:14:27.300
do they still go in,

444
00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:28.300
are the pins really set

445
00:14:28.300 --> 00:14:29.300
in.

446
00:14:29.300 --> 00:14:30.300
Just like it is,

447
00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:31.300
the way it should be,

448
00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:32.300
if the handle is somewhere strange,

449
00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:33.300
looks odd in the harness,

450
00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:34.300
something

451
00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:35.300
doesn't fit,

452
00:14:35.300 --> 00:14:36.300
and you can fix that

453
00:14:36.300 --> 00:14:37.300
when you pick up the harness,

454
00:14:37.300 --> 00:14:38.300
by checking the reserve setup first

455
00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:39.300
before putting it on.

456
00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:41.300
And for the 5-point check

457
00:14:41.300 --> 00:14:42.300
the simplest way

458
00:14:42.300 --> 00:14:43.300
is on the body itself,

459
00:14:43.300 --> 00:14:44.300
to start,

460
00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:45.300
we go from the inside

461
00:14:45.300 --> 00:14:46.300
outward,

462
00:14:46.300 --> 00:14:47.300
namely

463
00:14:47.300 --> 00:14:49.300
the reserve having been

464
00:14:49.300 --> 00:14:50.300
already checked,

465
00:14:50.300 --> 00:14:51.300
we then go on

466
00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:52.300
to all the others,

467
00:14:52.300 --> 00:14:53.300
our buckles,

468
00:14:53.300 --> 00:14:54.300
are they closed

469
00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:55.300
and secured.

470
00:14:55.300 --> 00:14:56.300
That includes

471
00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:57.300
the shoulder buckles,

472
00:14:57.300 --> 00:14:58.300
and also includes

473
00:14:58.300 --> 00:15:00.300
the helmet clasp.

474
00:15:00.300 --> 00:15:01.300
What's important is simply

475
00:15:01.300 --> 00:15:02.300
that all the buckles

476
00:15:02.300 --> 00:15:04.550
are closed and secured.

477
00:15:04.550 --> 00:15:05.550
Point 1,

478
00:15:05.550 --> 00:15:06.550
Point 2,

479
00:15:06.550 --> 00:15:07.550
we go further out

480
00:15:07.550 --> 00:15:08.550
from ourselves,

481
00:15:08.550 --> 00:15:09.550
outward,

482
00:15:09.550 --> 00:15:10.550
namely to the risers,

483
00:15:10.550 --> 00:15:11.550
are they not twisted,

484
00:15:11.550 --> 00:15:12.550
do they run

485
00:15:12.550 --> 00:15:13.550
for those lines

486
00:15:13.550 --> 00:15:14.550
going up to the wing.

487
00:15:14.550 --> 00:15:15.550
Wing checked,

488
00:15:15.550 --> 00:15:16.550
in other words,

489
00:15:16.550 --> 00:15:17.550
we've sorted it,

490
00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:18.550
the cells

491
00:15:18.550 --> 00:15:19.550
based on what's needed,

492
00:15:19.550 --> 00:15:20.550
they lie here,

493
00:15:20.550 --> 00:15:21.550
like with the leading edge,

494
00:15:21.550 --> 00:15:23.550
and now we have point 3,

495
00:15:23.550 --> 00:15:24.550
the wing is laid out checked,

496
00:15:24.550 --> 00:15:25.550
meaning,

497
00:15:25.550 --> 00:15:26.550
the way we want it,

498
00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:27.550
is it nicely open

499
00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:29.550
and nicely aligned with the wind.

500
00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:30.550
And point 4

501
00:15:30.550 --> 00:15:31.550
we go to

502
00:15:31.550 --> 00:15:32.550
the wind direction,

503
00:15:32.550 --> 00:15:33.550
and important,

504
00:15:33.550 --> 00:15:34.550
as for strength: nothing

505
00:15:34.550 --> 00:15:35.550
— if we don't have

506
00:15:35.550 --> 00:15:36.550
the right direction,

507
00:15:36.550 --> 00:15:38.550
but a 50-something headwind,

508
00:15:38.550 --> 00:15:40.550
or a 20-something tailwind,

509
00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:41.550
then in terms of strength

510
00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:43.550
it's definitely not right.

511
00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:46.030
And point 5

512
00:15:46.030 --> 00:15:48.030
is the launch strip

513
00:15:48.030 --> 00:15:49.030
and

514
00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:51.260
the area around it is free.

515
00:15:51.260 --> 00:15:52.260
For that,

516
00:15:52.260 --> 00:15:53.260
we check quickly again,

517
00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:54.260
in the air,

518
00:15:54.260 --> 00:15:55.260
yes,

519
00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:56.260
no pilots coming in to land in front of us.

520
00:15:56.260 --> 00:15:58.260
And also the launch strip

521
00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:00.260
really is clear.

522
00:16:00.260 --> 00:16:01.260
Pesky things

523
00:16:01.260 --> 00:16:02.260
like children

524
00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:03.260
or animals

525
00:16:03.260 --> 00:16:04.260
who could suddenly,

526
00:16:04.260 --> 00:16:05.260
during the launch procedure,

527
00:16:05.260 --> 00:16:07.260
run across your launch strip.

528
00:16:07.260 --> 00:16:08.260
If that's the case,

529
00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:10.260
then wait, send people away,

530
00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:11.260
kids out of the way,

531
00:16:11.260 --> 00:16:13.260
wait until the animals have walked past,

532
00:16:13.260 --> 00:16:14.260
the dogs,

533
00:16:14.260 --> 00:16:15.260
the cows grazing,

534
00:16:15.260 --> 00:16:17.260
and only then launch.

535
00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:18.260
Imagine,

536
00:16:18.260 --> 00:16:19.260
if we, with a mass —

537
00:16:19.260 --> 00:16:20.260
let's say,

538
00:16:20.260 --> 00:16:21.260
I'm 80 kg,

539
00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:22.260
with the paraglider

540
00:16:22.260 --> 00:16:23.260
and all the gear,

541
00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:24.260
then I'm at about 100 kg total.

542
00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:25.260
And me,

543
00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:26.260
going at 20 km/h,

544
00:16:26.260 --> 00:16:28.260
is a kinetic energy

545
00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:29.260
that for whoever

546
00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:30.260
I'd hit

547
00:16:30.260 --> 00:16:31.260
becomes very quickly

548
00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:34.340
seriously dangerous.

549
00:16:34.340 --> 00:16:35.340
Important,

550
00:16:35.340 --> 00:16:37.340
if we do a reverse launch,

551
00:16:37.340 --> 00:16:38.340
we've got good wind,

552
00:16:38.340 --> 00:16:40.340
we can do the reverse launch,

553
00:16:40.340 --> 00:16:41.340
then we turn around in the harness

554
00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:43.340
after the 5-point check

555
00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:44.440
to face the wing,

556
00:16:44.440 --> 00:16:46.440
now from points 1 to 4,

557
00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:47.440
nothing changes much,

558
00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:48.440
but what I want to come back to

559
00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:49.440
is namely:

560
00:16:49.440 --> 00:16:50.440
the launch strip,

561
00:16:50.440 --> 00:16:51.440
checking the airspace,

562
00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:52.440
and a free strip,

563
00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:53.440
immediately,

564
00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:54.440
right before the reverse launch,

565
00:16:54.440 --> 00:16:55.440
point 5,

566
00:16:55.440 --> 00:16:56.440
normally,

567
00:16:56.440 --> 00:16:59.180
repeat it again well.

568
00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:01.180
Then we go slowly

569
00:17:01.180 --> 00:17:02.180
into

570
00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:04.300
the launch,

571
00:17:04.300 --> 00:17:05.300
and as I

572
00:17:05.300 --> 00:17:06.300
rightly mentioned,

573
00:17:06.300 --> 00:17:07.300
that is to say,

574
00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:09.300
the three-phase launch.

575
00:17:09.300 --> 00:17:10.300
And it starts with

576
00:17:10.300 --> 00:17:12.300
the inflation phase,

577
00:17:12.300 --> 00:17:13.300
after that comes

578
00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:16.300
the control and correction phase,

579
00:17:16.300 --> 00:17:18.300
and then comes the acceleration phase.

580
00:17:18.300 --> 00:17:20.300
And it's really important

581
00:17:20.300 --> 00:17:22.300
that we think this through in those three steps.

582
00:17:22.300 --> 00:17:23.300
Many pilots,

583
00:17:23.300 --> 00:17:24.300
at the launch site,

584
00:17:24.300 --> 00:17:25.300
are way ahead in their head,

585
00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:26.300
they're already a little airborne,

586
00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:27.300
there's

587
00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:28.300
already the acceleration.

588
00:17:28.300 --> 00:17:29.300
Then we say:

589
00:17:29.300 --> 00:17:30.300
first, do point 1,

590
00:17:30.300 --> 00:17:31.300
do point 2 well,

591
00:17:31.300 --> 00:17:32.300
then inflate,

592
00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:34.300
control and correct,

593
00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:35.300
and then

594
00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:36.300
I decide,

595
00:17:36.300 --> 00:17:37.300
does it fit,

596
00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:38.300
is everything

597
00:17:38.300 --> 00:17:39.300
the way I want,

598
00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:40.300
do I feel safe,

599
00:17:40.300 --> 00:17:41.300
all good,

600
00:17:41.300 --> 00:17:43.300
then comes the acceleration phase.

601
00:17:43.300 --> 00:17:45.300
And you shouldn't do all the three-phase moves at once,

602
00:17:45.300 --> 00:17:47.300
because the control and correction phase

603
00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:49.300
is exactly there

604
00:17:49.300 --> 00:17:51.300
for us to spot a mistake.

605
00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:52.300
The wing is,

606
00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:53.300
for example,

607
00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:55.300
we've got a knot in the line,

608
00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:57.300
we've got something

609
00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:58.300
that's not right,

610
00:17:58.300 --> 00:17:59.300
we abort.

611
00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:01.690
If we're already in the acceleration phase,

612
00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:02.690
already in it,

613
00:18:02.690 --> 00:18:04.690
I wouldn't really do a full abort anymore,

614
00:18:04.690 --> 00:18:05.690
because as we said,

615
00:18:05.690 --> 00:18:06.690
in acceleration

616
00:18:06.690 --> 00:18:07.690
we're moving fast.

617
00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:08.690
And the area

618
00:18:08.690 --> 00:18:10.690
where we ideally want to be airborne quickly,

619
00:18:10.690 --> 00:18:11.690
namely in the air,

620
00:18:11.690 --> 00:18:13.690
because once in the air, we're safer,

621
00:18:13.690 --> 00:18:15.690
we have no obstacles coming at us,

622
00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:16.690
we could trip,

623
00:18:16.690 --> 00:18:17.690
go into the air,

624
00:18:17.690 --> 00:18:18.690
everything fine again.

625
00:18:18.690 --> 00:18:19.690
Important is,

626
00:18:19.690 --> 00:18:21.690
do 1 and 2 well,

627
00:18:21.690 --> 00:18:23.690
and then decide:

628
00:18:23.690 --> 00:18:24.690
yes, well,

629
00:18:24.690 --> 00:18:25.690
is the acceleration good,

630
00:18:25.690 --> 00:18:26.690
or no,

631
00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:27.690
doesn't fit — abort.

632
00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:28.690
By the way,

633
00:18:28.690 --> 00:18:30.690
on a practical exam,

634
00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:33.690
as long as you abort in point 1 or point 2,

635
00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:35.690
that's a perfectly fine abort, no problem.

636
00:18:35.690 --> 00:18:38.690
If you abort in point 3, the acceleration phase,

637
00:18:38.690 --> 00:18:39.690
abort,

638
00:18:39.690 --> 00:18:41.690
then you haven't done point 2 properly,

639
00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:43.690
and then you get a negative point

640
00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:44.690
for the acceleration phase check.

641
00:18:44.690 --> 00:18:49.110
Important is,

642
00:18:49.110 --> 00:18:50.110
afterwards,

643
00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:51.110
when you've

644
00:18:51.110 --> 00:18:52.110
got takeoff speed,

645
00:18:52.110 --> 00:18:53.110
reached it,

646
00:18:53.110 --> 00:18:54.110
and we lift off,

647
00:18:54.110 --> 00:18:56.370
very important,

648
00:18:56.370 --> 00:18:57.370
that after takeoff

649
00:18:57.370 --> 00:18:59.370
we don't let our brakes go.

650
00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:01.370
We keep seeing this in practice,

651
00:19:01.370 --> 00:19:02.370
people on flights

652
00:19:02.370 --> 00:19:03.370
and relatively quickly

653
00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:04.370
want

654
00:19:04.370 --> 00:19:06.370
to get comfortable in the harness,

655
00:19:06.370 --> 00:19:08.370
and good for us but not for the comfort,

656
00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:09.370
but it's dangerous,

657
00:19:09.370 --> 00:19:10.370
the issue,

658
00:19:10.370 --> 00:19:11.370
because we let the brakes go,

659
00:19:11.370 --> 00:19:13.370
and now you suddenly have

660
00:19:13.370 --> 00:19:14.370
a disturbance,

661
00:19:14.370 --> 00:19:15.370
which maybe wasn't noticeable during launch,

662
00:19:15.370 --> 00:19:17.370
or a lot of crosswind,

663
00:19:17.370 --> 00:19:19.370
and the wing relatively quickly

664
00:19:19.370 --> 00:19:20.370
pulls to the side.

665
00:19:20.370 --> 00:19:22.370
And that's plainly connected to the front,

666
00:19:22.370 --> 00:19:23.370
and so,

667
00:19:23.370 --> 00:19:24.370
sit yourself in first,

668
00:19:24.370 --> 00:19:25.370
settle into the harness,

669
00:19:25.370 --> 00:19:27.370
make yourself comfortable first,

670
00:19:27.370 --> 00:19:28.370
when you're far

671
00:19:28.370 --> 00:19:30.370
well into the planned direction,

672
00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:32.370
where your intended flight goes,

673
00:19:32.370 --> 00:19:34.370
have plenty of air and room,

674
00:19:34.370 --> 00:19:37.370
then you can let the brakes go briefly

675
00:19:37.370 --> 00:19:38.370
and get comfortable

676
00:19:38.370 --> 00:19:40.370
and pick the brakes back up afterwards,

677
00:19:40.370 --> 00:19:41.370
in turn.

678
00:19:41.370 --> 00:19:43.370
Now there's also the situation

679
00:19:43.370 --> 00:19:45.370
where right after launch you notice

680
00:19:45.370 --> 00:19:47.370
that we're not flying straight,

681
00:19:47.370 --> 00:19:49.370
but veering right or left.

682
00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:51.370
That can have various causes,

683
00:19:51.370 --> 00:19:52.370
for example,

684
00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:54.370
that already at launch

685
00:19:54.370 --> 00:19:55.370
you weren't in the fall line,

686
00:19:55.370 --> 00:19:57.370
but launched into the wrong direction.

687
00:19:57.370 --> 00:19:58.370
Could be,

688
00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:00.370
that you didn't look forward,

689
00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:01.370
have a knot in the line,

690
00:20:01.370 --> 00:20:03.370
or it could be

691
00:20:03.370 --> 00:20:04.370
that you have strong crosswind,

692
00:20:04.370 --> 00:20:07.370
blowing your tip against the one side.

693
00:20:07.370 --> 00:20:08.370
Most important of all,

694
00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:10.370
that actually in the 3-phase launch

695
00:20:10.370 --> 00:20:12.370
is point 4.

696
00:20:12.370 --> 00:20:14.370
And point 4 is

697
00:20:14.370 --> 00:20:16.370
the proper stabilizing,

698
00:20:16.370 --> 00:20:17.370
that you do.

699
00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:19.370
You've found your direction,

700
00:20:19.370 --> 00:20:21.370
and that has to be the absolute priority.

701
00:20:21.370 --> 00:20:23.370
Regardless of what the cause is,

702
00:20:23.370 --> 00:20:25.370
that you can fly off to the side.

703
00:20:25.370 --> 00:20:27.370
First, weight shift well,

704
00:20:27.370 --> 00:20:29.370
if needed brake on the opposite side

705
00:20:29.370 --> 00:20:30.370
firmly enough,

706
00:20:30.370 --> 00:20:31.370
to fly straight,

707
00:20:31.370 --> 00:20:32.370
to fly far, far,

708
00:20:32.370 --> 00:20:35.370
to get plenty of distance between us and the ground,

709
00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:38.370
and then deal with the problem.

710
00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:44.370
If, if you don't have that,

711
00:20:44.370 --> 00:20:45.370
front or otherwise,

712
00:20:45.370 --> 00:20:47.370
it's pretty hopeless, namely,

713
00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:48.370
that you uncontrolled

714
00:20:48.370 --> 00:20:50.370
head back to the slope,

715
00:20:50.370 --> 00:20:52.370
and depending on the terrain,

716
00:20:52.370 --> 00:20:54.370
obviously not smart,

717
00:20:54.370 --> 00:20:56.370
to land there.

718
00:20:56.370 --> 00:20:59.370
Landing I would not prefer.

719
00:20:59.370 --> 00:21:02.370
I'd always head into open airspace

720
00:21:02.370 --> 00:21:03.370
to fly,

721
00:21:03.370 --> 00:21:05.370
because that gives me time to react.

722
00:21:05.370 --> 00:21:06.370
And that's good,

723
00:21:06.370 --> 00:21:08.370
the bigger the time window,

724
00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:10.370
the more calmly you can address the problem.

725
00:21:10.370 --> 00:21:13.370
And then you have to react accordingly.

726
00:21:13.370 --> 00:21:14.910
Correct is,

727
00:21:14.910 --> 00:21:16.910
when you have a problem,

728
00:21:16.910 --> 00:21:17.910
let's say,

729
00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:19.910
we have a knot in the line,

730
00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:21.910
even though we did our check properly,

731
00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:23.910
and we even

732
00:21:23.910 --> 00:21:25.910
did the 3-phase launch state 2 well,

733
00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:27.910
namely control and correction,

734
00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:30.910
and then we develop a knot in the line

735
00:21:30.910 --> 00:21:31.910
that we didn't see

736
00:21:31.910 --> 00:21:33.910
and now we're flying out there.

737
00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:35.910
Important is: stabilize,

738
00:21:35.910 --> 00:21:37.910
fly straight,

739
00:21:37.910 --> 00:21:39.910
as we've discussed,

740
00:21:39.910 --> 00:21:42.910
and apropos knots in the line.

741
00:21:42.910 --> 00:21:44.910
There's probably no pilot

742
00:21:44.910 --> 00:21:46.910
who hasn't had a knot at some point.

743
00:21:46.910 --> 00:21:48.910
Or that's a bit of a stretch.

744
00:21:48.910 --> 00:21:49.910
It's something

745
00:21:49.910 --> 00:21:51.910
you simply get from this:

746
00:21:51.910 --> 00:21:53.910
because we have loose lines,

747
00:21:53.910 --> 00:21:55.910
and mostly during line sorting at launch,

748
00:21:55.910 --> 00:21:57.910
I have rocks lying around,

749
00:21:57.910 --> 00:21:58.910
or tall grass,

750
00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:00.910
they can form a knot.

751
00:22:00.910 --> 00:22:02.910
It's not tragic,

752
00:22:02.910 --> 00:22:04.910
as long as you know what to do.

753
00:22:04.910 --> 00:22:06.910
Get out into open airspace,

754
00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:08.910
now I start dealing with the problem,

755
00:22:08.910 --> 00:22:10.910
and now let's see, what's the problem?

756
00:22:10.910 --> 00:22:12.910
I recognize, aha,

757
00:22:12.910 --> 00:22:14.910
I actually do have a knot.

758
00:22:14.910 --> 00:22:16.910
When I have the knot,

759
00:22:16.910 --> 00:22:19.170
then I can decide,

760
00:22:19.170 --> 00:22:21.170
do I clear the knot,

761
00:22:21.170 --> 00:22:23.170
there are various aids

762
00:22:23.170 --> 00:22:25.170
to open the knot.

763
00:22:25.170 --> 00:22:26.170
It can be, for example,

764
00:22:26.170 --> 00:22:29.170
that I give a pulse with the brake on the knot side,

765
00:22:29.170 --> 00:22:31.170
in the pulse.

766
00:22:31.170 --> 00:22:33.170
It could be that the knot opens up.

767
00:22:33.170 --> 00:22:35.170
There's the stabilizer line,

768
00:22:35.170 --> 00:22:37.170
in Austrian color,

769
00:22:37.170 --> 00:22:39.170
mostly the trim line,

770
00:22:39.170 --> 00:22:41.170
or the stabilizer line,

771
00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:43.170
or I can also,

772
00:22:43.170 --> 00:22:45.170
for a knot, for example, at the front,

773
00:22:45.170 --> 00:22:47.170
with a collapse,

774
00:22:47.170 --> 00:22:49.170
a 50% collapse,

775
00:22:49.170 --> 00:22:51.170
which we'll get back to later,

776
00:22:51.170 --> 00:22:53.170
if you do that,

777
00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:55.170
I can unload the wing so much

778
00:22:55.170 --> 00:22:57.170
that the chance is high

779
00:22:57.170 --> 00:22:59.170
that the knot opens up again.

780
00:22:59.170 --> 00:23:01.170
When the knot opens,

781
00:23:01.170 --> 00:23:03.170
and you can fly straight from this state,

782
00:23:03.170 --> 00:23:05.170
then you can hold it so that

783
00:23:05.170 --> 00:23:07.170
you fix the weight,

784
00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:09.170
the tip against the brake,

785
00:23:09.170 --> 00:23:11.170
and fly straight,

786
00:23:11.170 --> 00:23:13.170
then we can decide.

787
00:23:13.170 --> 00:23:15.170
And if we can answer the question with 100%:

788
00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:17.170
yes, you can answer it,

789
00:23:17.170 --> 00:23:19.170
then we do it.

790
00:23:19.170 --> 00:23:21.170
Then we go in and land.

791
00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:23.170
But if we're unsure,

792
00:23:23.170 --> 00:23:25.170
then we show,

793
00:23:25.170 --> 00:23:27.170
so, flying straight,

794
00:23:27.170 --> 00:23:29.170
I can show that

795
00:23:29.170 --> 00:23:31.170
you quickly get overwhelmed.

796
00:23:31.170 --> 00:23:33.170
Then it absolutely makes sense,

797
00:23:33.170 --> 00:23:35.170
as long as you've still got steering, over a large field,

798
00:23:35.170 --> 00:23:37.170
ideally not over forest,

799
00:23:37.170 --> 00:23:39.170
to fly to a big meadow,

800
00:23:39.170 --> 00:23:41.170
and then go for the reserve.

801
00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:43.170
Reserve situations we'll cover later.

802
00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:45.170
But we've mentioned it here already.

803
00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:47.360
Dog curves.

804
00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:49.360
Dog curves is also one of those things

805
00:23:49.360 --> 00:23:51.360
you want to avoid,

806
00:23:51.360 --> 00:23:53.360
because they ultimately cost flight time.

807
00:23:53.360 --> 00:23:55.360
And the time,

808
00:23:55.360 --> 00:23:57.360
in other words we end up with less altitude at the point,

809
00:23:57.360 --> 00:23:59.360
if we're heading to a point,

810
00:23:59.360 --> 00:24:01.360
and we just have wind,

811
00:24:01.360 --> 00:24:03.360
then we can simply head straight for it,

812
00:24:03.360 --> 00:24:05.360
and we can keep just as much altitude,

813
00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:07.360
nicely high, as we wanted.

814
00:24:07.360 --> 00:24:09.360
But if we have a wind component from the side, from the left,

815
00:24:09.360 --> 00:24:11.360
and we just fly straight at the point,

816
00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.360
then we get a so-called dog curve,

817
00:24:13.360 --> 00:24:15.360
which as we've said in the theory section,

818
00:24:15.360 --> 00:24:17.360
is a big detour,

819
00:24:17.360 --> 00:24:19.360
and then we can reach the point

820
00:24:19.360 --> 00:24:21.360
as we wanted.

821
00:24:21.360 --> 00:24:23.360
That's why we need a wind correction angle.

822
00:24:23.360 --> 00:24:25.360
A wind correction angle is nothing other than

823
00:24:25.360 --> 00:24:27.360
a flight path you choose.

824
00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:29.840
And if we choose a little

825
00:24:29.840 --> 00:24:31.840
into the wind,

826
00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:34.840
then we make a nice straight line toward the point,

827
00:24:34.840 --> 00:24:38.840
and we can reach it optimally.
